                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Sooo, only apply enough DOTs along with pet damage (if kiting) until the mob turns, usually at about 12% to 15% or so. Then pull your pet OFF, and make sure the only DOT left on the mob is Dark. You don't want the mob to die just yet. You can keep your low level Dark on the mob so he doesn't go anywhere (or keep him rooted), and just let your CoB, or in my case, Arch Lich, get your mana bar full, reapplying Dark as needed. Then cast your Life Tap DOT to get your HPs up. Hopefully the mob still has a percent or two left, so you can continue to convert HPs to mana if needed and then cast another Life Tap DOT. Remember, you get full HPs from the Life Tap DOT even if the mob only has 5 HPs left. When you have gotten your mana up as high as the mobs remaining HPs will allow, go ahead and have your pet finish the mob off.<br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />What is the difference between artificial holding the mob unkilled while medding up, or medding up after having killed it? It's the same downtime either way. Your HP regeneration? why dont you kill that current prey and Lifetap/DoT the actual next one up?<br /><br /><br /><br /><br />Yag.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
